9. SMOKE TEST #7 — IN PROGRESS / S3 SYNC PERFORMANCE PROBLEM
================================================================================

  Smoke test #7 launched at ~16:48 UTC with both fixes deployed (rev-4
  managed templates: ECS stop guard + narrowed S3 include filters).

  Pipeline submitted 3 jobs (2x AWS_DOWNLOAD, 1x get_software_versions).
  A fresh r8g.2xlarge spot worker (i-00f55b99ca3876c11) provisioned, but
  after 20+ minutes all 3 jobs were still RUNNABLE — the worker was still
  syncing 65 GiB / 30k objects from S3 before ECS could start.

  Problem: spot instances are idling (and costing money) for 20+ minutes
  just copying database files before doing any useful work. The S3 sync
  of 30k small files is inherently slow regardless of include filters.

  Decision: switch to a custom AMI with databases pre-baked. This
  eliminates boot-time sync entirely — workers come online and start
  processing immediately.

================================================================================
10. AMI vs EFS DECISION
================================================================================

  Brainstormed two alternatives to the S3 sync:

  Custom AMI (pre-baked databases) — CHOSEN
    Pros: fastest boot (seconds), best read perf (local SSD), no ongoing infra,
          no throughput charges, automated Packer build
    Cons: must rebuild AMI (~30 min) on DB version bumps (few times/year),
          region-specific, snapshot cost (~$3.75/mo)

  EFS (shared NFS filesystem) — REJECTED
    Pros: no AMI rebuilds, instant mount, update DBs in one place
    Cons: NFS latency kills Bowtie2/DIAMOND random-seek performance (same
          reason ADR-001 rejected it), throughput costs at scale, monthly cost
          even when idle

  Key factor: databases change only a few times per year, so AMI rebuild
  overhead is negligible. The I/O performance advantage of local SSD is
  preserved (core rationale from ADR-001).

  Created: issues/I14-custom-ami-worker.md
  Updated: infra/adr-001-db-placement.md (status → Superseded)

